pr_review_body:
Nice, thank you!
I remember I looked at the `PYTHON_VERISONS` line last night, but I missed it!

@henryiii Do you happen to know how much trouble it is to make our pre-commit codespell catch VERISONS, iterater, VISIBLITY ... even if only part of a longer name put together with underscores?

@vcarpani Thanks for the changes. Apologies it took me a bit to review but I was on my annual leave.

I left one more comment to ensure we follow the same patterns as on the rest of the code-base. This is not just a matter of styling but also to ensure that the solution aligns with other building systems that are used internally at Meta. Once you have it, to be on the safe side, I think it's also worth it for us to test it internally and confirm that nothing breaks. Give me a shout when ready and I'll do this for you.

Again thanks for the contribution and apologies for the long delay.

Couple of tiny things.

This Overall this looks great, and is ready to merge from my POC.

@florianfischer91 are you happy with it? If so, let's merge.

Thanks a lot for working on this, it looks very good! I left a few comments inline. 

Another more general comment: I like the result including a blend with uncorrected data using the `DayNightCompositor` (although a bit too blue), but in principle, the method `pyspectral.rayleigh.Rayleigh.reduce_rayleigh_highzenith` is doing the same thing as this blend with uncorrected. The only, yet significant, difference is that the `DayNightCompositor` does the scaling across the blending area in `cos(sunz)`-space, whereas in this PR the scaling is in `sunz`-space. Could you try and see what happens if you convert the `sunz`, `lim_low` and `lim_high` to cosine-space before sending them them to `reduce_rayleigh_highzenith`?

@simonrp84 what did you actually have in mind for the implementation in pyspectral? To do the scaling with `sunz` or `cos(sunz)`?

@NicolasHug Thanks, the changes look good.

How would you feel about adding in the metrics of each weights a single `epe` field that stores the value of the "most appropriate" experiment. Note that this idea implicitly exists already in all other models. For example the `acc@1` usually reports the value on the validation set used for training; there are others we could be reporting (or example ImageNet Real/V2 for classification) but currently dont. This way you can have a single metric that summarizes the model metrics and move the per-dataset breakdown on a separate list. I've provided some examples of this previously at https://github.com/pytorch/vision/pull/5859#discussion_r856143326

We don't have to solve this now but we need to fix this before the release to avoid BC breakages on the future.

I left some initial comments; 

High level comment is; 

- The manager class APIs seem a bit brittle (especially with cache). Can we use ABCClass to have abstract methods? I also think we should hide cache behind the manager's create/delete APIs.
- Cache means the agent becomes stateful, which means the behavior after agent restarts is undefined. Is there a design for how to handle this? Also, if we don't handle this right now, can we make this feature off by default? We shouldn't have non-fully working feature just for the sake of performance optimization, especially when the feature is already GA

This looks good now and is in my opinion safe to be merged.

It actually follows our [second goal](https://github.com/django-json-api/django-rest-framework-json-api#goals) to be compatible with DRF as much as possible.

@n2ygk I hope my inline explanations make sense and I suggest we merge this. Otherwise let me know.

It still doesn't support v1. Add these tests, please, so we can sure that we will always support all versions.

```python
    def test_v1(self):
        result = JavaStatusResponse.build(
            {
                "description": {"text": "A Minecraft Server"},
                "players": {"max": 20, "online": 0},
                "version": {"name": "1.12.2", "protocol": 340},
                "modinfo": {
                    "type": "FML",
                    "modList": [
                        {"modid": "minecraft", "version": "1.12.2"},
                        {"modid": "mcp", "version": "9.42"},
                        {"modid": "FML", "version": "8.0.99.99"},
                        {"modid": "forge", "version": "14.23.5.2859"},
                    ],
                },
            }
        )

        assert result.forge_data == ForgeData(
            fml_network_version=1,
            channels=None,
            mods=[
                ForgeDataMod(modid="minecraft", modmarker="1.12.2"),
                ForgeDataMod(modid="mcp", modmarker="9.42"),
                ForgeDataMod(modid="FML", modmarker="8.0.99.99"),
                ForgeDataMod(modid="forge", modmarker="14.23.5.2859"),
            ],
            truncated=False,
        )

    def test_v2(self):
        result = JavaStatusResponse.build(
            {
                "description": {"text": "A Minecraft Server"},
                "players": {"max": 20, "online": 0},
                "version": {"name": "1.13.2", "protocol": 404},
                "forgeData": {
                    "fmlNetworkVersion": 2,
                    "channels": [],
                    "mods": [
                        {"modId": "forge", "modmarker": "ANY"},
                    ],
                },
            }
        )

        assert result.forge_data == ForgeData(
            fml_network_version=2,
            channels=[],
            mods=[ForgeDataMod(modid="forge", modmarker="ANY")],
            truncated=False,
        )

    def test_v3(self):
        result = JavaStatusResponse.build(
            {
                "enforcesSecureChat": True,
                "forgeData": {
                    "channels": [],
                    "mods": [],
                    "truncated": False,  # TODO add test for truncated
                    "fmlNetworkVersion": 3,
                    "d": bytes.fromhex(
                        "5e0000e0a084e390a4e78d8be39996e2b98ce1a698ccbae2b8b1e681a4e492b8e2a191e29ba7e6b2aee5a"
                        "999e3a8b9e789a5e0b088e384b5e0a69ae28280e6b2aee5a999e3a8b9e789a5e0b088e384b5e0a69ae581"
                        "80e6b380e5b29be38ab3e48483e38a9ce580b1e2ad8be79ca6e6b9abe1b29be392bae69daee68886e482b"
                        "8e2a081dcb0e2b68ee5b49ae1a281e384ae02"
                    ).decode("utf8"),
                },
                "description": {"text": "A Minecraft Server"},
                "players": {"max": 20, "online": 0},
                "version": {"name": "1.20.1", "protocol": 763},
            }
        )

        assert result.forge_data == ForgeData(
            fml_network_version=3,
            channels=[
                ForgeDataChannel(res="minecraft:unregister", version="FML3", required=True),
                ForgeDataChannel(res="minecraft:register", version="FML3", required=True),
                ForgeDataChannel(res="forge:tier_sorting", version="1.0", required=False),
                ForgeDataChannel(res="forge:split", version="1.1", required=True),
            ],
            mods=[
                ForgeDataMod(modid="minecraft", modmarker="1.20.1"),
                ForgeDataMod(modid="forge", modmarker="ANY"),
            ],
            truncated=False,
        )
```

Thanks for this PR!

This seems like an acceptable solution to me. I still find it strange that `__contains__` and `keys()` return inconsistent results, but I accept that behavior is desired for some stores.

@madsbk, please complete the TODO checklist (or cross out irrelevant items).

I did not review `colorbynone2` so I am not sure if my comment is found on a proper ground but having a listener attached to a data structure this way (given two way binding) feels a bit unfortunate.

There were few things you've considered but did you consider having a module level singleton dispatcher object that you use to subscribe and unsubscribe?

```ts
// dispatcher.ts

type EventKey = string;
const listeners: Map<EventKey, Function> = new Map();

export function addListener(type: string, fn: Function) {
  ...
}

export function dispatch(type: string) {
  ...
}
```

@smeng9 hello,
This  PR is being superseded by a larger scope update that is partially observable via  #8405
FYI

@bjgill Hey, thanks for the PR! I think this is great work, and I'm in favour of cleaning up our exceptions anyway.

This is a great start, we've not played around with typing in notify before but it'd be cool for us to get mypy checking on PRs for this repo too, though I notice there's a couple of failing lines in json parsing that we handle by catching `AttributeError`s at the moment. But I think this is a good start towards getting a more consistent approach to errors.

I'll get this merged and deployed early next week.

This is very, very cool! And I think that it would probably resolve #16763 in a more general manner.

The idea behind #16763 was to allow for stronger `@union`-centric APIs, including allowing `Field`s to have computable defaults.

@benjyw and @thejcannon have the most experience with the AST APIs, so I'll defer to them.
